assessment_details.task_description:
This assessment task has a strong reflective component. Your reflections need to:

contain detailed descriptions of incidents/issues/challenges/successes you encountered during your workplace experience, and how you reacted to them;

discuss your frustrations and consequent growth with regards to the incidents/issues/challenges/successes you chose to document;

ask probing questions about yourself and your future work options;

reflect on how your workplace experience may impact your future career choices.

PART 1: OVERVIEW OF THE WORKPLACE EXPERIENCE (300 to 600 words)

Provide a brief overview focused on the following:

Yourself, your major, your career plans at this stage;

Your motivational style, personality type, conflict resolution style (you may use and refer to the measures/instruments in the Measures folder on BlackBoard);

Dates of internship;

Your placement organisation, including its size, structure, industry, brief history, and culture (you may use and refer to the culture diagnostic in the Measures folder on BlackBoard);

Your supervisor - their position in the organisation, their supervisory style (participative, democratic etc);

Tasks/projects allocated, their value (or not) as a learning and development opportunity; and

Your expectations about the graduate attributes required for the placement upon starting the placement, as opposed to the realities after settling into the placement.

PART 2: JOURNAL REFLECTIONS (400-600 words per journal entry)

NOTE: You are required to complete three (3) formative reflective journal entries. You will need to seek timely feedback from fellow students, a mentor, or someone you have worked with as you complete reflections. After consideration of the feedback you received and incorporating comments/suggestions, you need to CHOOSE ONE ENTRY for inclusion in your summative assessment.

Following are some themes that might be used for the journal entries:

the organisation, its culture, and its style of supervision;

how you used your knowledge and attributes;

challenging work tasks;

how you developed your graduate attributes;

how you developed your employability through requesting and responding to feedback;

the role and support of your supervisor;

the role and support of your colleagues;

your role and how you support others and add value;

how you are reacting to being managed by your supervisor and others;

the type of work you have been undertaking, and whether this is the type of work for the next stage of your career.

Journal entry #1: Using the SEAL method, reflect on your INITIAL workplace experiences regarding your developing employability skill-set.

Look at the graduate attributes indicated on the ECP and discuss the graduate attributes and skills that you brought with you to the workplace and how you used them. You should also research and determine appropriate graduate attributes for your profession.

Journal entry #2 : Again, using the SEAL method, reflect on another workplace experience but this time, choose one where you experienced a FAILURE .

Critically evaluate your performance, reflect on what you learned from this experience, and indicate how this experience and learning has assisted you with your developing employability skill-set and relates to appropriate graduate attributes for your profession.

Journal entry #3 : Again, using the SEAL method, reflect on a workplace experience, this time with a focus on one where you achieved SUCCESS .

Critically evaluate your performance, reflect on what you learned from this experience, and indicate how this experience and learning has assisted you with your developing employability skill-set and relates to appropriate graduate attributes for your profession.

PART 3: KEY LEARNINGS (100-200 words)

Finally, provide a short summary paragraph that highlights three (3) key lessons learned so far: Two lessons about yourself, and one lesson about the nature of work and organisations.

REFERENCING:

Use a standard referencing system (eg, APA, Harvard)

Include a reference list of all cited literature

Incorporate a minimum of 3 relevant academic references.

course_introduction:
RBUS3999 is a Work Integrated Learning (WIL) course that provides students with the opportunity to apply their conceptual knowledge to the real world via a professional placement or industry project. The placement allows you to integrate your theoretical and conceptual knowledge with the skills and problem-solving techniques required in the work place. As such, the course is particularly focused on enabling you to develop your employability skills, gain knowledge, understand the attitudes of business professionals, grow your professional network, and engage with real world business issues.

What is employability?

The University of Queensland has an employability framework that focuses on four themes:

Awareness - understanding employability as both degree knowledge and the attributes that guide workplace performance;

Experiences - engaging with a range of experiences to develop the skills and attributes for employability;

Learning - uses self-reflection to translate experiences into employability development; and

Transfer - communicating employability effectively in the recruitment process and transferring learning into workplace performance.

This means that during this course, you will have the opportunity to:

understand your skills, strengths and areas for development;

work on specific projects in an organisation, and develop your role within that organisation;

work with a range of diverse people, and assist others and teams with tasks;

apply employability skills, and practice your skills to develop them further;

reflect on the skills and qualities that enhance your employability; and

develop a personal value proposition.

Why is Business Industry Placement Important?

This course will enable you to undertake an industry work placement of 80 to 120 hours throughout (or before) the semester to gain greater insight into working in organisations to apply and enhance your employability. You should find your own work placement in a functional area of management practice in an organisation that is willing to host you and provide meaningful project work to further develop your skills and abilities. Support is also available from the BEL Faculty Employability Team to help you source an appropriate host organisation. Alternatively, you may engage in an industry project, where it is expected that you would need to contribute 80 to 120 hours throughout the semester on your team project.

The changing nature of work and employers’ needs necessitate a flexible approach to internships. As an example, you might choose to complete your internship in one block of 3 or 4 weeks full-time, or due to other commitments you may need to complete your internship 2 days a week over 7-8 weeks or 3 days a week over 4-5 weeks. It is your responsibility to negotiate your working hours with your industry host, as well as manage your time effectively to attend four (4) seminars throughout the semester. NOTE: Completing one day a week of your internship hours is not recommended as experience has shown the likelihood of you being given realistic work tasks and/or being included in the work team is significantly reduced .

Your employability and career success are important outcomes of your degree. The Business Industry Placement aims to develop awareness of your employability strengths, development needs and how to create an action plan to strengthen these needs. Thus, it is structured to promote a valuable industry placement/project, real work experiences and assist in bridging your transformation from student to reflective practitioner.

Course Changes in Response to Previous Student Feedback

Feedback from students resulted in changes to the weighting of assessment items, as well as the nature of assessment 3. There is now greater recognition that assessments 2 and 3 should be about different issues, with assessment 2 focusing on workplace experiences and assessment 3 focusing on personal development planning. S upervisor reports are no longer assessed as part of assessment 3. The weighting of assessment 1 has been reduced.
